{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and negative impacts of using prescribed fire as a peatland management tool?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across peatlands, studies reported that prescribed burning (sometimes along with other interventions) reduced tree/shrub cover in fens in the USA and UK (1763) and that heather cover in bogs was lower in plots burned more often or than in unburned plots in the UK and Germany (1774). Burning increased plant species richness or diversity in a fen (USA) and a bog (New Zealand) in replicated, controlled studies (1763), but other studies found plant species richness was reduced or limited in a bog (UK) and fens (USA; with other interventions) (1774), and typically unaffected in a fen (UK; with other interventions) (1763). In fens, burning reduced forb cover and increased sedge/rush cover with no effect on grass cover in one replicated, controlled study (USA), whereas another replicated before-and-after study (UK; with other interventions) reported reduced grass/sedge/rush cover (1763). In bogs, moss cover (including Sphagnum) was higher in plots burned more often in one UK bog, and burning increased moss/lichen/bare ground cover 2\u20137 months after burning in Germany (1774). For herbaceous plants in bogs, burning had no short-term effect on cottongrass in Germany, increased cottongrass after 8\u201318 years in the UK, and resulted in similar cottongrass cover when burned every 10 or 20 years in the same UK bog; burning reduced purple moor grass in Germany and had mixed effects on other grass-like plants and forbs across sites (1774). Vegetation structure responses included more biomass of grass-like plants but less total vegetation, shrub and bryophyte biomass in plots burned more frequently in a UK bog (1774). Characteristic fen mosses and herbs were typically unaffected by burning (with other interventions) in one UK fen (1763).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1763",
    "1774"
  ]
}

