{
  "query": "What are the typical effects of rewetting on the vegetation of drained peatlands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across 36 studies of rewetting without planting, vegetation often shifted from drier grassland communities toward more wetland/peatland-characteristic communities; some studies found little or no change, and rewetted sites sometimes differed from natural peatlands [1756]. Sphagnum moss cover or abundance frequently increased (with some mixed or no effects reported), while non\u2011Sphagnum moss cover often showed no change or declined in some cases; Sphagnum growth was reported to reach natural levels in forested fens [1756]. Herb cover commonly increased, including sedges, cottongrasses, and some reeds/rushes; purple moor grass often decreased; one study reported no effect on total herb cover [1756]. Tree/shrub cover typically decreased or showed no change, though increases were reported in some fens; effects could be mixed among species [1756]. Overall vegetation cover sometimes increased, sometimes decreased, or showed no change depending on site [1756]. Plant species richness/diversity often increased, but many studies found no effect and some reported reductions; compared with natural peatlands, rewetted sites sometimes had lower richness, sometimes higher, and sometimes similar [1756]. In studies where rewetting was combined with tree removal, results also included increases in wetland\u2011characteristic plants and herbs (including sedges and cottongrasses), increases in Sphagnum in some cases, and reductions in non\u2011Sphagnum or forest mosses; effects on species richness ranged from increases to no change [1732].",
  "action_ids": [
