{
  "query": "To maintain disturbance in fens and fen meadows, how does the effect of cutting/mowing compare with using grazing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across fens and fen meadows, cutting/mowing has been evaluated more extensively (14 studies) than grazing (4 studies) [1759][1762]. Mowing often altered overall plant community composition (six replicated studies) and increased cover of fen- or wet meadow\u2011characteristic plants (four studies); it frequently increased total moss/bryophyte cover (four of six studies), reduced cover/abundance of some herbs (e.g., bindweed, reeds, sedges, purple moor grass, grass\u2011like plants; six replicated studies), sometimes reduced shrub cover (two of three studies), and often increased overall plant species richness (eight studies) [1759]. One study reported that mown fen meadows had similar vegetation structure to grazed meadows [1759]. For grazing, a replicated, paired, site comparison found that overall plant community composition differed between grazed and mown fen meadows, and that grazed meadows contained fewer plant species and fewer fen\u2011characteristic species than mown meadows [1762]. Before\u2011and\u2011after studies reported grazing increased cover of some herb groups (cottongrasses, sedges or all grass\u2011like plants), with mixed effects on purple moor grass; shrub cover was reduced in one study but typically unchanged in another; fen\u2011characteristic moss cover was unchanged in one study while Sphagnum cover decreased in another; plant species richness increased after grazing was reinstated in one study but typically showed no effect in another [1762].",
