{
  "query": "What interventions are available to restore peatland vegetation on sites previously used for commercial forest plantations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Identified interventions include: (1) cutting/removing/thinning forest plantations, which in replicated studies increased cover of some herbs such as cottongrasses and sedges, reduced cover of forest-characteristic mosses, and increased total plant species richness in rich fens, with mixed effects on Sphagnum cover depending on site conditions [1731]. (2) Cutting/removing/thinning trees combined with rewetting peat, which in multiple studies altered plant community composition to be less like drained, forested sites; increased abundance of wetland-characteristic plants; often increased Sphagnum cover while reducing non\u2011Sphagnum or forest-characteristic mosses; increased cover of some herbs including cottongrasses and sedges; increased ground vegetation height in one study; reduced numbers of tall trees shortly after intervention; and in some cases increased plant species richness (though some studies found no change) [1732]. (3) Stabilizing the peat surface (e.g., pegging coconut fibre rolls onto bare peat) to aid colonization, which in one study did not change total vegetation, moss, shrub, or cottongrass cover compared to controls [1815].",
