{
  "action_id": "1771",
  "action_title": "Change season/timing of cutting/mowing",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nTwo studies evaluated the effects on peatland vegetation of mowing or cutting in different seasons. One study was in a fen meadow\u00a0and one was in a peatland with mixed vegetation.\nPlant community composition (2 studies): One replicated, randomized, paired, before-and after study in a fen meadow in the UK reported that changes in plant community composition were typically similar in spring-, summer- and autumn-mown plots. However, one study in a peatland in the Netherlands\u00a0reported that summer- and winter-mown areas developed cover of different plant community types.\nOverall plant richness/diversity (1 study): One replicated, randomized, paired, before-and after study in a fen meadow in the UK\u00a0found that plant species richness increased more, over two years, in summer-mown plots than spring- or autumn-mown plots."
}

{
  "action_id": "696",
  "action_title": "Maintain traditional water meadows (includes management for breeding and/or wintering waders/waterfowl)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nFour studies from Belgium, Germany, the Netherlands and the UK (including two site comparisons of which one also replicated) found that maintaining traditional water meadows resulted in an increased population size or number of territories of northern lapwing, common redshank and black-tailed godwit and increased plant species richness. However one of these studies also found common snipe declined on all sites under management to maintain traditional water meadows,\u00a0and another of the studies found that differences in numbers of birds were present before meadow bird management.\nTwo studies (a replicated study and a review of European studies) found that managing traditional water meadows by grazing had mixed impacts on wildlife and that the productivity of northern lapwings was too low to sustain populations on three of the four water meadows managed for waders. A randomized, replicated, controlled trial in the Netherlands found that cutting in June maintained relatively stable vegetation and a review found mowing could be used to maintain water meadows but had variable effects on plant species richness.\nOne replicated site comparison from the Netherlands found more birds bred on 12.5 ha plots with management for wading birds (in combination with per-clutch payments), however at the field scale there was no difference in bird abundance or species richness between conventionally managed fields and those managed for birds."
}

{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and trade-offs of using traditional management practices like mowing or grazing to maintain biodiversity in fen meadows?",
  "relevant_summary": "- In a fen meadow, summer mowing increased plant species richness more over two years than spring or autumn mowing, while overall community composition changes were typically similar across seasons (1771).\n- In fen meadows, grazing produced plant communities that differed from mown sites and sometimes had fewer total plant species and fewer fen\u2011characteristic species than mown meadows (1762). After reinstating grazing, plant species richness increased in one study but showed no typical effect in another; grazing increased some herb groups (e.g., sedges, cottongrasses) and reduced purple moor grass in one case, but effects on shrubs were mixed (reduced in one study, no effect in another) and Sphagnum cover decreased in one study (1762).\n- Maintaining traditional water meadows increased plant species richness in one study, but reviews noted mowing had variable effects on plant richness; cutting in June maintained relatively stable vegetation (696). For birds, management to maintain traditional water meadows increased numbers or territories of some waders (northern lapwing, common redshank, black\u2011tailed godwit), but common snipe declined on managed sites, and productivity of northern lapwings on grazed meadows was too low to sustain populations in most sites studied (696).\n- For butterflies, species richness and abundance were similar between wet meadows managed by annual autumn mowing and by light cattle/horse grazing; starting cattle grazing reduced bog fritillary emergence and use in one case, while intermediate\u2011intensity cattle grazing had higher marsh fritillary caterpillar web abundance than low or high intensity, and occupancy by marsh fritillary caterpillars was similar across grazed, burned, and unmanaged fen meadows (3971).",
