{
  "action_id": "1807",
  "action_title": "Reprofile/relandscape peatland (without planting)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nOne study evaluated the effects of reprofiling/relandscaping peatlands (without planting) on peatland vegetation. The study was in degraded bogs (being restored as fens).\nPlant community composition (1 study): One site comparison study in Canada\u00a0reported that after five years, reprofiled (and rewetted) bogs contained a different plant community to nearby natural fens.\nVegetation cover (1 study): The same study reported that after five years, reprofiled (and rewetted) bogs had lower vegetation cover (Sphagnum moss, other moss and vascular plants) than nearby natural fens."
}

{
  "action_id": "1811",
  "action_title": "Disturb peatland surface to encourage growth of desirable plants (without planting)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nTwo studies evaluated the effects of disturbing the peat surface (without planting) on peatland vegetation. Both studies were in fens.\nPlant community composition (2 studies): Two replicated, paired, controlled, before-and-after studies (one also randomized) in fens in Germany\u00a0and Sweden\u00a0reported that soil disturbance affected development of the plant community over 2\u20133 years.\u00a0In Germany, disturbed plots developed greater cover of weedy species from the seed bank than undisturbed plots. In Sweden, the community in disturbed and undisturbed plots became less similar over time.\u00a0\nCharacteristic plants (2 studies): The same two\u00a0studies reported that wetland- or fen-characteristic plant species colonized plots that had been disrturbed (along with other interventions). The study in Germany noted that peat-forming species did not colonize the fen."
}

{
  "query": "What are the typical outcomes for vegetation when the upper layer of degraded peatland soil is removed or disturbed without subsequent planting?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple studies, removing the upper layer of peat/soil led to plant communities that differed from unstripped sites, with outcomes influenced by stripping depth [1809]. Following removal, cover of wetland- or peatland\u2011characteristic plants often increased over 4\u201313 years, and fen\u2011characteristic plant richness increased in one replicated comparison [1809]. Rush, reed, or sedge cover commonly increased within 2\u20136 years, while purple moor grass cover decreased for 2\u20135 years in two controlled studies; one study found no effect on sedge or bentgrass cover after five years [1809]. Vegetation biomass was reduced for up to 18 years in two studies, though another study reported no effect after four years [1809]. Total plant species richness frequently increased over 2\u201318 years, though results were mixed across sites and studies, and richness increased over time after stripping in one study [1809]. Disturbing the peat surface (without planting) altered plant community development over 2\u20133 years; in one study, disturbance promoted greater cover of weedy seed\u2011bank species, and in another, disturbed and undisturbed communities diverged over time [1811]. Disturbed plots saw colonization by wetland/fen\u2011characteristic species in both studies, but peat\u2011forming species did not colonize in one fen [1811]. Reprofiling degraded bogs (without planting) produced plant communities different from nearby natural fens and resulted in lower Sphagnum, other moss, and vascular plant cover after five years [1807].",
  "action_ids": [
